{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ac039172-0903-4a9c-9be1-2f0053b99b0a","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap those static calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling the statics directly. In tests, you mock or stub it:\n\n```csharp\nvar fs = new Mock<IFileSystem>();\nfs.Setup(f => f.ReadAllText(\"config.json\")).Returns(\"{\\\"key\\\":\\\"value\\\"}\");\n```\n\n**Alternatively**, the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` with a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own wrapper.\n\n**Key benefits:**\n- Tests run fast (no disk I/O)\n- No temp file cleanup headaches\n- Easy to simulate errors (permissions, missing files, etc.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c4e308d-bb3f-4b4f-a72e-e691ec5ab114","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their code. This is a common design question about testability.\n\nLet me give them a concise, practical answer about the standard approach: introducing an abstraction (interface) over file system operations and using dependency injection.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"340A:6A01C:79AA347:866D0D5:69F4090F"},"id":"6d0b3176-0d85-4b3a-a406-000cb4fd70ae","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:59:52.501Z","parentId":"a8573a47-8e11-4294-8fa1-df383afd9964"}
